  <h4>If Your Have Trouble Concentrating</h4>
  We get it. 
  With everything going on around you, it's tempting to check your Snapchat or just watch one Netflix episode.
  <ul>Here's some helpful ideas to improve your concentration:
  <br><br>
   <li>Relax your brain. Taking deep breaths before starting difficult tasks always helps.</li>
  <li>Make a designated work space in an area that it free of distractions (ex. dog,phone,television). Don't be afraid to customize this space!</li>
  <li>Turn off ALL electronic devices and put them away. It's much easier to concentrate without the constant notifications.</li>
  <li>If you want to have some background music, go ahead. Just make sure you don't get caught up in your favorite song that you forget everything.</li>
  <li>Take some short breaks in between. Sometimes your brain can get overwhelmed, which results in giving up or procrastination.</li>
</ul>
  
  <br><br>
  <br><br>
  
  <h4>If You Have Procrastination Problems</h4>
  Sometimes, school can be pretty overwhelming. 
  With all of the projects, essays, tests, quizes, and not to mention homework EVERY SINGLE NIGHT, your just feel like pushing it all until the night of the due date (and sometimes, hours before).
  <ul>Here's how to prevent/decrease procrastination:
  <br><br>
  <li>The most important thing is to not punish yourself for procrastination. 
  That decreases self-confidence, which is obviously a very important trait to have to accomplish anything.</li>
  <li>Break down your tasks into small chunks. Big jobs become easier to tackle if you take small steps.</li>
  <li>Start with the hardest tasks. If you start easy, it becomes hard to complete harder things later in the day.</li>
  <li>Although this might sound silly, give yourself a talk. Hype yourself up to create confidence in completing tasks.</li>
  <li>Lastly, the most important of them all, reward yourself. Your brain will start to recognize rewards and will prevent uou from more procrastination.</li>
   </ul>
   
